 Uber is the worldâ€™s most valuable startupâ€”now valued at close to $51 billion, according to the Wall Street Journalâ€”and the undisputed king of the ride-hailing industry. At least at the moment. But outside the US, where Uber is most aggressively seeking growth,Â its overseas rivals are increasingly banding together in a bid to hamper its rapid expansion. On Monday, Reuters reported that Chinese ride-hailing giant Didi Kuaidi had invested in Ola, the biggest ride-summoning app in India. The amount was not disclosed, though the Times of India, citing unnamed sources, previously reported that Didi Kuaidiâ€™s stake in the company would be around $30 million. Ola confirmed the investment to WIRED but not the amount. Didi Kuaidi did not immediately respond to a request for comment. Didi Kuaidiâ€™s investment comes right on the heels of the announcement of its partnership with US-based Lyft. Earlier in the month in New York, the two companies revealed they would link their apps. Lyft users traveling in China could hail Didi Kuaidi drivers from their Lyft app, and vice versa. The feature is set to go live by early 2017. But theÂ partnership appears to go beyond apps. Didi Kuaidi alsoÂ reportedly invested $100 million in Lyft earlier this year. It has also invested in the Singapore-based ride-hailing company GrabTaxi. All of this cooperation among Uberâ€™s rivals signalsÂ the emergence of consolidation as the key strategy forÂ challenging the global juggernaut that is Uber. As Uberâ€™s most formidable competitor in Chinaâ€”the companyâ€™sÂ most covetedÂ marketâ€”Didi Kuaidi is in a prime position to lead this charge, and itâ€™s not shying away from the task.Â Consolidation is also in the interest of Uber rivalsâ€™ deep-pocketed investors. Chinese tech giants Alibaba and Tencent, for instance, have a stake in Didi Kuaidi and Lyft, and Japan-based SoftBank hasÂ investments in Ola and Didi Kuaidi. Uber has made no secret of wanting to own the Chinese market, recently raising $1.2 billion in fresh funding to pour into its China operations. It has also expressed a special interest in India, now the worldâ€™s fastest growing major economy. But its rivals are determined to create at least a few bumps alongÂ Uberâ€™s road to global dominance. The slew of worker misclassification lawsuits filed against on-demand companies just wonâ€™t stop. On Wednesday, class-action complaints were filed against on-demand food delivery companies DoorDash and GrubHub in California state court, alleging that the drivers should not be considered independent contractors, as their companies have deemed them, but official employees. Shannon Liss-Riordan, a Boston-based labor lawyer, filed the suits against the two companies, seeking class action status. She also brought forward a complaint in arbitration against Caviar, a curated food delivery service owned by Jack Dorseyâ€™s company Square. The Caviar complaint is a little different in that Liss-Riordan represents only one San Francisco driver. After filing a class action complaint against Caviar earlier this year, Liss-Riordan explains, the court ruled that the arbitration clause in Caviarâ€™s written agreement was enforceable, requiring workers to resolve their disputes through an arbitration process, per complaint, rather than lumping the cases together in a class-action suit. â€œThereâ€™s a lot of commonality among these cases,â€ Liss-Riordan tells WIRED. â€œCompanies basically hope to massively save on labor costs by classifying their workers as independent contractors rather than employees.â€ That brings the tally of companies Liss-Riordan has brought complaints against to 11, which includes on-demand ride-hailing companies Uber and Lyft, laundry service Washio, home services Homejoy and Handy, grocery delivery service Instacart, and on-demand delivery services Postmates and Shyp, in addition to DoorDash, GrubHub and Caviar. So far, only the case against Uber has been certified as a class action. Of these companies, a coupleâ€”Instacart and Shypâ€”have reclassified part of its workforce in what looks to be a reaction to pressure from these filings. One company, Homejoy, shut down, citing the suits as a â€œdeciding factorâ€ in the decision. The class-action suits against on-demand ride-hailing services Uber and Lyft are the furthest along in the process. On September 1, a federal judge in San Francisco granted class-action status to a lawsuit brought by three Uber drivers against the on-demand ride company. (Uber is appealing that decision.) Lyft, meanwhile, faces a similar suit, with its class certification hearing in December. â€œAll of these companies seem to be watching what other companies are doing,â€ Liss-Riordan says, â€œand thinking they can get away with it.â€ You can read the complaints filed against DoorDash, GrubHub and Caviar below. // <![CDATA[
