 Uber on Tuesday filed to appeal a ruling by a federal judge in San Francisco to grant class-action status to a lawsuit brought by three Uber drivers against the on-demand ride company. On September 1, US District Judge Edward Chen decided that Uber drivers in California could join the case seeking mileage and tip reimbursement from the company. The drivers can also collectively challenge the company on the main issue of worker misclassificationâ€”whether they should be considered employees of Uber under the law, rather than independent contractorsâ€”which could have far-reaching implications for the on-demand economyâ€™s basic business model. The lawsuit against Uber is the furthest along of a slew of recent cases against on-demand companies, including Lyft, Caviar, Postmates and Homejoy, among others. These startups employ freelance contractors, or 1099 contract workers, instead of employees, arguing that this can make the work more flexible than a structured, 9-to-5 job. But as of late, critics have been calling for better protection for these workers, who lack benefits such as Social Security, Medicare, and workersâ€™ compensation. Others, meanwhile, also point out that companies who employ this business model stand to save on payroll taxes, undercutting other on-demand tech firms who do make an effort to classify their workers as employees. Uber has largely stuck to the same arguments it used in court. It is â€œmanifestly erroneousâ€ that the suit has been certified as a class, the company says, because there is no such thing as a typical Uber driver. That lumps the issues of thousands of drivers into a single suit, Uber argues, whereas there are substantial differences in how drivers use its platform. Beyond that, the company insists, converting Uber drivers to employees would cost the drivers the flexibility they love, because it upends Uberâ€™s business model. The appeal (see below) is worth perusing in full. But in case youâ€™d like to skip to the juiciest parts, weâ€™ve added comments to the document for extra context.   DV.load("//www.documentcloud.org/documents/2424873-2015-09-15-as-filed-oconnor-rule-23-f-petition.js", {  width: 532,    height: 600,    sidebar: false,    text: false,    container: "#DV-viewer-2424873-2015-09-15-as-filed-oconnor-rule-23-f-petition"  }); 2015 09 15 as Filed Oâ€™Connor Rule 23(F) Petition (PDF)
2015 09 15 as Filed Oâ€™Connor Rule 23(F) Petition (Text) Ride-hailing giant Uber has lost another battleÂ in the incendiary debate overÂ whether or not its drivers should be considered employees. Officials at Californiaâ€™s Employment Development Department (EDD) recently determined that an ex-Uber driver qualified asÂ an employee of the company, not an independent contractor, and as such wasÂ entitled to unemployment benefits. To be sure, itâ€™s one decision by one state agency and only applies to one individual. But an administrative law judge backed the decision on appeal, and UberÂ ultimately decided not to fight further. â€œWe disagreed with the decision, but since it only affects one person â€¦we decided to focus on the bigger picture,â€ an Uber spokesperson tells WIRED. That bigger picture is a federal lawsuit filed against Uber that was granted class-action status earlier this monthÂ seeking to gain Uber drivers recognition as employees of the company, not independent contractors. This latest decision is not the first time a state agency has determined an Uber driver was an employee. In May, the Florida Department of Economic Opportunity found that Uber driver Darrin McGillis was an Uber employee and thus eligible for unemployment insurance. In June, the California Labor Commission, which investigates wage claims, decided that ex-Uber driver Barbara Ann Berwick was entitled to unpaid wages and reimbursement for business expenses in the nine weeks she worked as an Uber driver last year. Shannon Liss-Riordan, the Boston lawyer who is representing the Uber drivers in the class-action suit against the company, has cited the California Labor Commissionâ€™s decision in her arguments in court. She says this and other decisions by state agencies solidify her sideâ€™s stance. â€œThis California decision supports our argument that when a fact-finder sits down to look at the facts, and applies California laws, Uber drivers are employees,â€ Liss-Riordan says. For its part, Uber says that other states have determined Uber drivers are independent contractors rather than employees of the company, including labor or unemployment boards in Georgia, Arizona, Pennsylvania, Colorado, Indiana, Texas, New York, Illinois, and Californiaâ€”where at least one decision, the company says, came from the EDD itself. Back in February, Uber announced a strategic partnership with Carnegie Mellon Universityâ€™s robotic research group: an initiative the ride-hailing service said was meant to help it develop driverless-car technology. Now, in an apparent move to deepen that alliance, Uber has just revealedÂ that it is giving $5.5 million to the university to support a new robotics faculty chair as well as sponsor three graduate fellowships. â€œWeâ€™re pumped to be part of a growing innovation ecosystem in Pittsburgh that includes world leading research institutions and companies, as well as an increasing number of start-ups,â€ Travis Kalanick, Uberâ€™s CEO, said in a blog post announcing the endowment. Itâ€™s an interesting move from Uber, the undisputed giant of ride-hailing apps, and a company that has gained notoriety for its obsession with growth. Even after five years, the company is still expanding rapidly;Â in spite of regulatory hurdles, itâ€™s stillÂ muscling its way into new markets, both in the US and abroad. But anotherÂ reason for Uberâ€™s outpouring of generosity could be its, ahem, unique relationship with Carnegie Mellon. Not too long after the announcement of their partnership, according to several reports, Uber hired away dozenâ€™s of CMUâ€™s scientists, leaving one of the worldâ€™s top robotics institutions in a crisis. Some viewed Uber luring these researchers away as a good thing, certifying the academic institution as a place of opportunity. Indeed, Uber has provided desirable jobs to researchers from other, more unconventional sources in the past, including hiring the two hackers who wirelessly hijacked an Internet-connected Jeep. But others may see the move more as a way to make amends with Carnegie Mellon. And certainly, with competitors like Google bearing down on Uberâ€™s as-yet-unattained dream â€œto make transportation as reliable as running waterâ€ (read: self-driving cars), the ride-hailing giant needs all the allies it can get. Uber may have finally found a friend in New York Cityâ€™s government after all. Today, the cityâ€™s Comptroller, Scott Stringer, wrote in a post on Medium that the City Council should postpone its vote on a bill that would temporarily cap the number of new driver licenses available to companies like Uber and Lyft. An arbitrary cap on for-hire vehicles is not the answer â€“ we need to think strategically about our transport networks http://t.co/QzSI8Q9yoW â€” Scott M. Stringer (@scottmstringer) July 21, 2015  The cityâ€™s plan calls for studying the impact of ride-hailing services on traffic congestion before approving new licenses. But Stringer says that approach gets it all backwards. The plan, he says, â€œseems to ignore the fact that so many other factorsâ€Šâ€”â€Šfrom economic growth to street designâ€Šâ€”â€Šaffect congestion.â€ Stringer said in a speech today he had met with David Plouffe, the political strategist who has been leading Uberâ€™s campaign against the bill, which New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio has fiercely defended.Â But the comptrollerÂ didnâ€™t let Uber completely off the hook, writing that both Uber and the city need to come to the negotiating table. â€œWe must take a close look at wage standards in the shared economy,â€ Stringer wrote, â€œand reexamine the Cityâ€™s traditional cab drivers and their working conditions, which for decades have been defined by long hours, low wages, and few, if any benefits.â€ Uber CEO Travis Kalanick wants you to know that Uber is great. So great, in fact, New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio should abandon any effort to cap the companyâ€™s growth. The mayorÂ has called for a limit to the number of licenses available to ride-sharing companies like Uber while the city studies the impact of the influx of car services on traffic. Uber is vociferously opposed to the ideaâ€”the companyâ€™s New York general manager even challenged de Blasio to a public live-streamed debate. (The mayorÂ declined.) Now, Kalanick has taken to Twitter, a time-honored tactic in his companyâ€™s frequent battles with city governments. Once a singularly outspoken tweeter, Kalanick has quieted as Uberâ€™s value has skyrocketed. But over the past week, via a storm of retweets, heâ€™s made sure to call out the stories and anecdotes that appear to support Uberâ€™s side (including at least one WIRED story). Hereâ€™s a sampling: How @Uber saved me from cabs http://t.co/0EI6Asm1Kp â€” Errol Louis (@errollouis) July 21, 2015  @gawruff @hadip @coiascience I think you may be misinformedâ€¦ Every NY driver is commercially licensed by the TLC as are Uberâ€™s operations â€” travis kalanick (@travisk) July 21, 2015  @hadip @coiascience @deBlasioNYC Uber pays for more insurance, pays more in taxes, and uber drivers make more per hour â€” travis kalanick (@travisk) July 21, 2015  Laura Washington: Uber upends problem of â€˜hailing while blackâ€™: http://t.co/Xf8ywQNTV4 â€” Corey C Owens (@coreycowens) July 20, 2015 Â  Is Bill de Blasioâ€™s crusade against Uber standing in the way of social progress? @jheil weighs in: VIDEO: http://t.co/jMXMcHdRaR â€” Joe Scarborough (@JoeNBC) July 20, 2015  An army of preachers in New York defending Uber for the opportunity it provides to minorities pic.twitter.com/F5jmkPeEQD â€” Comfortably Smug (@ComfortablySmug) July 20, 2015  deBlasio could hedge bets by at least including his Uber referral code every time he mentions the company â€” Hunter Walk (@hunterwalk) July 20, 2015  On call with tech CEOs + me pre-election, Bill de Blasio said his #1 priority as mayor â€“> expand economic opportunity for regular people. â€” Marc Andreessen (@pmarca) July 20, 2015  De Blasio is making New York look terrible for tech. Like starting a company in France. https://t.co/iEXzJBTbHj â€” Jd Ross (@justindross) July 19, 2015  Watch now: Mayor @BilldeBlasio, donâ€™t leave New Yorkers stranded. https://t.co/No4ghRt4Lk â€” Uber NYC (@Uber_NYC) July 17, 2015  Among the many heated debates around on-demand ride-hailing services like Uber is whether they act as an antidote to the longstanding patterns of red-lining in the traditional taxi industry. According to one Uber-funded study released today, they do. Research group Botec Analysis found that summoning an UberX, the companyâ€™s budget tier, took less than half as long as calling for a taxi in several low-income neighborhoods in Los Angeles. Whatâ€™s more, the trips themselves cost less than half as much. Calling for an UberX was more reliable and wait times were shorter, according to the study. â€œThe answer was clear-cut, and consistent across neighborhoods and days,â€ writes study co-author Mark Kleiman. To gather data, pairs of riders called for a taxi and an Uber along pre-planned routes. The riders recorded the time between picking up the phone or opening an app and getting in a car. They also tracked how much each ride cost, then switched off. After each ride, whoever took a taxi last time took an Uber next time. Kleiman says the riders didnâ€™t know Uber had funded the effort but acknowledged that Uberâ€™s backing â€œmakes some skepticism about our results natural and proper.â€ â€œWe would be happy to share our data and methods with other research teams for re-analysis and replication,â€ he says. More independent study of the issue is a good idea. Kleiman acknowledges that his study didnâ€™t address many of the most trenchant questions around transit: the ethnicity of riders; riders with disabilities; or the lack of access for riders who donâ€™t have credit cards or smartphones. He says, â€œThis study ought to be the beginning of the scientific effort rather than the end.â€ New York Cityâ€™s Mayor Bill de Blasio is pushing a bill in the City Council that would put a cap on the number of driverâ€™s licenses available to companies like Uber â€¦ and now Uber is lashing out at the Mayor in the best way it knows how: through the Uber app. Uber has added a fake â€œde Blasioâ€ feature to its app, which is visible only to New York City Uber users. Cars are plentiful in UberPOOL and UberX mode, but on de Blasio mode, the map simply says â€œNo cars available.â€ Users who click on that message are greeted with another: â€œThis is what Uber will look like in NYC if Mayor de Blasioâ€™s Uber cap bill passes.â€  The City Council is expected to vote on the bill, which the de Blasio administration argues would curb traffic congestion in the city, by next week. So itâ€™s no surprise that Uber has also been buying up commercials on local television, with testimonies from hardworking drivers asking New Yorkers to protest the bill. Watch below:  During my last business trip, I skipped rental cars and cabs and took Ubers everywhereâ€”they were just so cheap! Turns out I wasnâ€™t the only one. Today, expense software company Certify released its lastest data on how business travelers are spending money. Their report found that for the first time, travelers used Uber more than traditional taxis. Uber accounted for 55 percent of ground transportation receipts submitted by employees versus 43 percent for taxis. (About 1 percent of receipts were for Lyft rides and another 1 percent for other ride-hailing services.) Thatâ€™s a reversal from last quarter, when Uber had 46 percent of the receipts versus 53 percent for taxis. The spike in Uber use is also taking a chunk out of the rental car business, according to the report. In the second quarter of 2014, 55 percent of people rented a car while traveling on business; that figure dropped by 10 percent during the same period this year. The receipts donâ€™t lie, Certify says: â€œUber is fast evolving to become the preferred choice of business travelers for ground transportation.â€
